data.content:
Kafka
A distributed streaming platform that retains events for a configured period, partitions topics, and provides various APIs.

Consumers
Entities that subscribe to and read streams of events from Kafka topics, always reading partition events in the order they were written.

Client Applications
Software that interacts with Kafka, reading and writing data from/to Kafka brokers simultaneously for scalability.

Event Key
An event key is a conceptual component of an event.<SEP>An identifier (e.g., customer or vehicle ID) used to ensure that events with the same key are written to the same topic partition.

Topics
Logical channels in Kafka to which events are published and from which consumers read; they are partitioned and can be replicated.

Events
Units of data published to Kafka topics, which are retained for a configurable duration instead of being deleted after consumption.

Traditional Messaging Systems
Systems where events are typically deleted immediately after consumption, unlike Kafka.

Kafka Brokers
Servers in a Kafka cluster where topic partitions are physically located, enabling distributed data storage.

Partitions
Divisions of a Kafka topic, spread across multiple Kafka brokers, enabling parallel processing and scalability.

Producers
Client applications that publish or write new events to Kafka topics and their partitions.

Geo-Regions
Geographical areas across which Kafka topics can be replicated to ensure data fault-tolerance and high availability.

Admin API (Kafka)
One of Kafka's five core APIs, used for managing and inspecting topics, brokers, and other Kafka objects.

Datacenters
Facilities across which Kafka topics can be replicated to provide fault tolerance and high availability for data.

Replication Factor
A configuration setting, commonly set to 3, that defines how many copies of topic-partition data are maintained for fault tolerance.

Consumer API (Kafka)
One of Kafka's five core APIs, used to subscribe to (read) one or more topics and process the event stream.

Producer API (Kafka)
One of Kafka's five core APIs, used to publish (write) a stream of events to one or more Kafka topics.

Kafka Streams API
One of Kafka's five core APIs, designed to implement stream processing applications and microservices with higher-level functions.

Kafka Documentation
Comprehensive information explaining Kafka's concepts in full detail.

Kafka Connect API
One of Kafka's five core APIs, used to build and run reusable data import/export connectors for integration with external systems.

Academic Papers (Kafka)
Scholarly articles providing in-depth understanding of Kafka.

Kafka Books
Published resources available for understanding Kafka in more detail.

Java (Language)
A programming language for which Kafka provides core APIs.

Scala (Language)
A programming language for which Kafka provides core APIs.

Kafka Quickstart
A guide offering hands-on experience to get started with Kafka.

Kafka Use Cases
Examples demonstrating how users globally are deriving value from Kafka.

Kafka Community
The Kafka community provides dozens of clients that augment those included with Kafka.<SEP>A worldwide network of users and contributors around Kafka.

Kafka Summit
The main conference of the Kafka community, featuring talks.

Data Import/Export Connectors
Reusable tools built using the Kafka Connect API to consume or produce streams of events from and to external systems.

Local Kafka Meetup Group
A community group for Kafka users to join and watch talks.

PostgreSQL
A relational database mentioned as an example of an external system that can integrate with Kafka via connectors.

Stream Processing Applications
Applications and microservices that can be implemented using the Kafka Streams API to process event streams.

External Systems
Other applications and systems that can integrate with Kafka using connectors to consume or produce event streams.

Topic Configuration Setting
A per-topic configuration setting in Kafka that defines for how long Kafka should retain events.

Data Size
A characteristic of data that Kafka's performance remains constant with respect to.

Network (Computing)
The infrastructure over which producer clients publish new events to Kafka topic partitions.

Scalability
The ability of Kafka to handle increased workloads, achieved by distributing topics over partitions and allowing client applications to read and write from many brokers simultaneously.

High Availability
A design principle ensuring continuous operation of Kafka data, supported by topic replication across multiple brokers, geo-regions, or datacenters.

Replication
The process of creating and maintaining multiple copies of Kafka topic-partition data to ensure fault-tolerance and high availability.

Fault Tolerance
A design principle ensuring that Kafka data remains available even if some components fail, achieved through topic replication.

Microservices
Small, independent services that can be implemented using the Kafka Streams API to process event streams.

Relational Database
Relational databases are existing systems that Kafka Connect can integrate with for continuous data import and export.<SEP>A type of database, such as PostgreSQL, that can integrate with Kafka via data import/export connectors.

Command Line Tooling (Kafka)
Tools provided by Kafka for management and administration tasks.

Apache Kafka
Apache Kafka is an event streaming platform described as a distributed system consisting of servers and clients that communicate via a high-performance TCP network protocol, offering capabilities to publish, subscribe, store, and process streams of events.

Event Streaming
Event streaming is the practice of capturing, storing, manipulating, processing, reacting to, and routing data in real-time as streams of events, serving as a technological foundation for automated software-defined businesses.

Kafka APIs (Collection)
A set of five core APIs provided by Kafka for Java and Scala, including Admin, Producer, Consumer, Streams, and Connect APIs.

Producer
Producers are client applications that publish or write events to Kafka, fully decoupled from consumers to achieve high scalability.

Consumer
Consumers are client applications that subscribe to, read, and process events from Kafka, operating independently from producers.

Event
An event records the fact that "something happened" and is the fundamental unit of data in Kafka, conceptually having a key, value, timestamp, and optional metadata headers.

Topic
A topic is a mechanism in Kafka for organizing and durably storing events, similar to a folder in a filesystem, supporting multiple producers and subscribers and retaining events for a configurable duration.

Kafka Cluster
A Kafka cluster is a distributed system comprising one or more servers that can span multiple datacenters or cloud regions, providing high scalability and fault tolerance for mission-critical use cases.

Broker
Brokers are servers within a Kafka cluster that form the storage layer, responsible for storing event streams.

Client
Clients are applications that allow users to write distributed applications and microservices to read, write, and process streams of events in parallel, at scale, and in a fault-tolerant manner.

TCP Network Protocol
The TCP network protocol is a high-performance protocol used by Kafka servers and clients for communication.

Kafka Connect
Kafka Connect is a component run on Kafka servers to continuously import and export data as event streams, integrating Kafka with existing systems like relational databases and other Kafka clusters.

Datacenter
Datacenters are physical locations where Kafka clusters can be deployed, potentially spanning multiple regions.

Cloud Region
Cloud regions are geographical areas in cloud environments where Kafka clusters can be deployed.

Kafka Streams Library
The Kafka Streams library is a higher-level client included with Kafka, available for Java and Scala, used for processing streams of events.

Event-Driven Architecture
Event-driven architecture is a software design pattern for which event streaming can serve as a foundation.

Data Platform
A data platform is a system for managing and processing data, for which event streaming can serve as a foundation.

Virtual Machine
Virtual machines are a deployment environment on which Kafka can be deployed.

Bare-Metal Hardware
Bare-metal hardware is a deployment environment on which Kafka can be deployed.

Event Source
Event sources are origins from which data is captured in real-time in the form of streams of events, such as databases, sensors, mobile devices, cloud services, and software applications.

Container
Containers are a deployment environment on which Kafka can be deployed.

Microservice
Microservices are a software development approach that can be built using Kafka clients and event streaming as a foundation.

Event Value
An event value is a conceptual component of an event.

Event Timestamp
An event timestamp is a conceptual component of an event.

Metadata Header
Metadata headers are optional conceptual components of an event.

Partition
A partition is a division of a topic, spreading it over a number of servers.

REST API
REST APIs are a method through which Kafka clients are available.

Programming Language
Programming languages are the environments for which Kafka clients are available.
